subsection.p:
As an example, we'll compute the sum
	\dfrac{2}{3} + \dfrac{3}{4}



We first find the lowest common denominator for the two fractions. The LCD is the smallest number that is a multiple of both 3 and 4, so in this example the LCD is 12.  


	Next, we build each fraction to an equivalent fraction with denominator 12. First, we multiply \dfrac{2}{3} by \dfrac{4}{4}. Because \dfrac{4}{4} is equal to 1, we have not changed the value of the fraction.  4 is called the building factor for \dfrac{2}{3}. Similarly, we multiply \dfrac{3}{4} by \dfrac{3}{3}.
		\dfrac{2}{3} \amp = \dfrac{2 \cdot \blert{4}}{3 \cdot \blert{4}} = \dfrac{8}{12} \amp \amp \blert{\text{The building factor is 4.}}
			\dfrac{3}{4} \amp = \dfrac{3 \cdot \blert{3}}{4 \cdot \blert{3}} = \dfrac{9}{12} \amp \amp \blert{\text{The building factor is 3.}}


The new fractions, \dfrac{8}{12} and \dfrac{9}{12}, are like fractions, so we add them by combining their numerators.
		\dfrac{2}{3} + \dfrac{3}{4} = \dfrac{8}{12} + \dfrac{9}{12} = \dfrac{8+9}{12} = \dfrac{17}{12}

